by The Realm of Hyrule » Fri Aug 06, 2021 11:04 am

The Messianic Kingdom wrote:Is it me or do the personalities of everybody’s characters feel like they’re a reflection of the user’s personality? e.g. when one of the user’s character(s) see a character they hate, they just make snarky, silver-tongued remarks like those popular high school girls in those cheesy teen movies you see on the Disney channel in the 2000s.

Am I overthinking this? Probably.


That's what I try my best to avoid, to be honest...
I have this philosophy that, if I am doing roleplay (Which F7 kinda is, and character creation is a distinct part of the process), I should try and distance myself IRL, and my characters as much as possible. There may always be elements that roleplay character and myself IRL may share, but usually they are different from myself. Because if I wanted to self-insert and hide it behind a character, I don't really consider that roleplaying, moreso 'faux' RP, because realistically... I'm just playing as myself, no?

That's why more often than not, I prefer making Female characters to RP as... It's the opposite of my gender, and thus I can more easy distance myself from IRL, and RP as a specific character because of that. The more I can pretend I am a fictional character in RP, the more interesting and less self-insert(ey) they are.
(Though recently, I have been having less trouble with character RP'ing as males, though some of my absolute favorites from the times I've RP'd are female)

Das Kaiserliche Vaterland wrote:
The Realm of Hyrule wrote:
That's what I try my best to avoid, to be honest...
I have this philosophy that, if I am doing roleplay (Which F7 kinda is, and character creation is a distinct part of the process), I should try and distance myself IRL, and my characters as much as possible. There may always be elements that roleplay character and myself IRL may share, but usually they are different from myself. Because if I wanted to self-insert and hide it behind a character, I don't really consider that roleplaying, moreso 'faux' RP, because realistically... I'm just playing as myself, no?

That's why more often than not, I prefer making Female characters to RP as... It's the opposite of my gender, and thus I can more easy distance myself from IRL, and RP as a specific character because of that. The more I can pretend I am a fictional character in RP, the more interesting and less self-insert(ey) they are.
(Though recently, I have been having less trouble with character RP'ing as males, though some of my absolute favorites from the times I've RP'd are female)
